{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2453"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2453"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.11,0.02,0.75,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78923"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2453"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64272"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1816"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43157"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78923"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic at 28 weeks of gestation for routine review. She is gravida 3, para 2, with previous uncomplicated pregnancies. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She feels well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her blood pressure is 160/110 mmHg, confirmed on repeat measurement two hours later. At her 24-week appointment, it was 130/90 mmHg. The fundal height is appropriate for gestational age. The fetal heart rate is 150/min. Cardiorespiratory and abdominal examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal full blood count, electrolytes, urea, creatinine, and liver function tests within reference ranges. Urinalysis shows no proteinuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassure and review in two weeks","Prescribe low-dose aspirin","Prescribe perindopril","Labetalol","Immediate delivery"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe gestational hypertension, defined as blood pressure \u2265160/110 mmHg after 20 weeks gestation. The absence of proteinuria or other organ dysfunction distinguishes this from pre-eclampsia. Prompt treatment is essential to prevent complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabetalol\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line antihypertensive medication for severe gestational hypertension. It is safe in pregnancy and effectively lowers blood pressure. After administration, blood pressure should be rechecked within 30 minutes to assess response and need for additional doses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassure and review in two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous in severe hypertension. These patients typically require admission for close blood pressure monitoring and assessment for development of pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-dose aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is used for prevention of pre-eclampsia but must be started between 12-20 weeks gestation. Starting at 28 weeks would be too late to provide benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E, like all ACE inhibitors, is absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy due to its teratogenic effects and risk of fetal renal damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate delivery\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for uncontrollable hypertension despite therapy, progressive organ dysfunction, or reaching 37 weeks gestation. At 28 weeks, the risks of prematurity outweigh the benefits unless there are severe complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating antihypertensive therapy, ongoing monitoring is essential to detect development of pre-eclampsia, which would be suggested by new proteinuria, elevated creatinine, abnormal liver function, or thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Labetalol is first-line treatment for severe gestational hypertension (BP \u2265160/110 mmHg)","ACE inhibitors are contraindicated in pregnancy due to teratogenicity","Low-dose aspirin for pre-eclampsia prevention should be started between 12-20 weeks gestation"],"references":["Gestational Hypertension and Preeclampsia: ACOG Practice Bulletin, Number 222. Obstet Gynecol. 2020 Jun;135(6):e237-e260. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32443079/","Lowe SA, Bowyer L, Lust K, McMahon LP, Morton M, North RA, Paech M, Said JM. SOMANZ guidelines for the management of hypertensive disorders of pregnancy 2014. Aust N Z J Obstet Gynaecol. 2015 Oct;55(5):e1-29. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26412014/","Buawangpong N, Teekachunhatean S, Koonrungsesomboon N. Adverse pregnancy outcomes associated with first\u2010trimester exposure to angiotensin\u2010converting enzyme inhibitors or angiotensin II receptor blockers: A systematic review and meta\u2010analysis. Pharmacology Research \u0026 Perspectives. 2020;8(5). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32815286/","Rolnik DL, Wright D, Poon LCY, Syngelaki A, O\u0027Gorman N, de Paco Matallana C, Akolekar R, Cicero S, Janga D, Singh M, Molina FS, Persico N, Jani JC, Plasencia W, Papaioannou G, Tenenbaum-Gavish K, Nicolaides KH. ASPRE trial: performance of screening for preterm pre-eclampsia. Ultrasound Obstet Gynecol. 2017 Oct;50(4):492-495. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28741785/","Melamed N, Ray JG, Hladunewich M, et al. Gestational hypertension and preeclampsia: are they the same disease? J Obstet Gynaecol Can 2014; 36:642. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25184984/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64272"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2453"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64272"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T11:34:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T11:34:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2453"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78923"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"",